	</form></div><span class="pb doctop" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0495">495<a style="padding-left: 5px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0495.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a></span><div class="doc">
      
      <h1>Luigi Pio to the American Commissioners</h1>
      <div class="docbody">
        <div class="opener">
          <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Messieurs</td>
		<td class="salutationRight"> Paris ce 22 janvier 1785.</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
        </div>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Ayant eu lhonneur de mettre sous les yeux du Roi mon matre Votre lettre du 27 7<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">bre.</span> 1784<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0294-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0294-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> et Sa Majest ayant fait mrement xaminer les propositions et les offres quelle contient,  l effet de lengager  conclure avec les Etats unis un trait damiti et de commerce, ma charg de Vous assurer que rien ne peut lui faire un plus grand plaisir, puisquelle donne tous ses soins  lagrandissement du commerce de son Royaume, tant intrieur quextrieur. Cest mme dans cette Vue que sa Majest a dernirement ouvert et tabli  Messine en sicile un port franc, dont toutes les nations sont invites  profiter, avec dautant plus dassurance quelles y seront reues et accueillies trs favorablement, et certaines dy jouir de toute sorte de privilges et immnits, comme ldit  joint Vous le prouvera.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0294-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0294-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> Je Vous prie, Messieurs, De Vouloir bien saminer les avantages qui peuvent rsulter pour Vos compatriotes en frquentant ce nouveau port.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Je suis en outre charg, Messieurs, de Vous faire au nom de sa Majest, une dclaration formelle que tous les btimens marchands, avec pavillon des tats unis, seront reus  Messine avec les marques de la plus sincre amiti, et quils y prouveront les effets de la plus grande hospitalit; Que pareillement dans tous les autres
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0496">[496<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0496.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
ports de sa domination, ils seront traits avec tous les gards possibles; quon Viendra toujours  leur secours, en leur fournissant tout ce dont ils auront besoin, et quils auront la libert dy Commercer, tant sur les productions de leur pays que sur les marchandises provenantes de leurs manufactures et de celles des autres nations.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Le Tabac tant la partie la plus essentielle du commerce de lAmrique, comme Vous mavs fait lhonneur de me lobserver dans un de nos entretiens particuliers; je dois Vous prvenir, Messieurs, que cette plante est devenue maintenant dans les tats du Roi mon matre un genre de commerce libre, par labolition de tous les droits auxquels elle tait ci devant sujette.  lgard des autres productions, Vous Aurs non seulement toute la libert de les introduire dans ses tats, et en aussi grande quantit que le porteront les demandes des Napolitains, mais encore celle dy faire Venir pour le reste de lItalie, du Levant et de toute autre contre, la quantit de marchandises que selon Vos spculations Vous jugers ncessaire; que Vous jouirs des mmes liberts et facilits pour exporter du Royaume de Sicile de lhuile, du Vin, des Soieries et toute autre production que les Siciles pourront vous fournir et qui seront pour Vous des objets dutilit et dagrment.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Le Roi mon matre na pas Voulu diffrer davantage  Vous donner, Messieurs, les marques les plus convaincantes du desir quil a davoir des liaisons avec les Etats unis, et  leur prouver sa bonne volont a entrer le plutt possible en relation de commerce avantageux pour les deux nations; se rservant sa Majest de prendre telles delibrations et rsolutions quil conviendra pour conclure dans toutes les formes un trait de commerce, Selon que Vous avez paru le desirer par Votre lettre.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">En attendant que ma cour puisse xaminer et peser mrement tous les objets qui sont  rgler dans un trait de cette nature, je crois, Messieurs, quil serait trs avantageux aux Amricains de commencer ds  prsent  frquenter les ports des Siciles, et particulirement celui de Messine, Pour y tablir toujours des relations de commerce, sur lesquelles on pourra ensuite stipuler plus prcisment dans le trait  faire.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Permettez, Messieurs, que je Vous observe encore que pour tablir et exercer un commerce de telle etendue quil soit, et dans tel pays que ce puisse tre il nest pas ncessaire dtre primitivement autoris par un trait: il suffit que les trangers y soient accueillis avec amiti et protgs par les loix et par le gouvernement. La preuve en est que toutes les nations qui font maintenant le
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0497">[497<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0497.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
commerce le plus tendu dans les Siciles, tels que les Anglais, les Francais, les Gnois, les Vnitiens, les Ragusiens, les hambourgeois, nont avec ma cour aucun trait de commerce; et quoiquil ny ait entrelle et la France quun commencement de trait, les Franais nen attendent point la conclusion, pour y faire un commerce des plus tendus et des plus avantageux.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Jai lhonneur dtre avec la considration la plus / distingue, / Messieurs, / Votre trs humble / et trs obeissant Serviteur</p>
        <div class="closer">
          <div class="signed-multiple">
    <p class="signed multiple">de Pio, charg des Affaires<br/>du Roy de Naples</p>
  </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="translation">
        <h2>TRANSLATION</h2>
        <div class="opener">
          <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Gentlemen</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Paris, 22 January 1785</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
        </div>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">I had the honor of putting before my lord the king your letter of 27 September 1784<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0294-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0294-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> inviting him to conclude a treaty of amity and commerce with the United States. His Majesty, having maturely examined the proposals and offers that it contains, has authorized me to assure you that nothing would please him more, as he gives all his attention to increasing the trade of his kingdom, internal as well as external. It is with this same view that his majesty recently opened and established a free port at Messina in Sicily by which all nations are invited to profit, the more so with assurance that they will be received and welcomed there very favorably and will be certain to enjoy all sorts of privileges and immunities, as the enclosed edict will demonstrate to you.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0294-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0294-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> I ask you, gentlemen, please to examine the advantages that can result for your countrymen from frequenting this new port.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">I am further charged, gentlemen, with making to you a formal declaration, in the name of His Majesty, that all merchant vessels under the flag of the United States will be received at Messina with marks of the most sincere friendship and impressions of the greatest hospitality, that they will be treated similarly in all the other ports under his dominion with all possible regard, that we will always come to their aid and furnish them with all that they might need, and that they will have liberty to trade produce of their own country as well as goods of their own manufacture and those of other nations.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Tobacco being the most essential part of American trade, as you did me the honor of observing during one of our private interviews, I must inform you, gentlemen, that this plant has now become in the dominions of my lord the king an item of free trade by the abolition of all duties to which it had previously been subject. With regard to other items of produce, you will have complete liberty not only to bring them into his dominions, and to do so in quantities as great as demand among Neapolitans will bear, but also to take merchandise from there to the rest of Italy, the Levant, and all other countries, in quantities that you, according to your own estimation,
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0498">[498<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0498.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
judge necessary. You will enjoy the same liberties and ease in exporting from the kingdom of Sicily oil, wine, silks, and all other produce that the Sicilians can furnish to you and that you might find of use or appeal.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">My lord the king did not want to delay any longer giving to you, gentlemen, the most convincing indications of his desire to have close connections with the United States and to prove to them his goodwill in entering as soon as possible into commercial relations advantageous to both nations, His Majesty reserving the right to take such decisions and resolutions as he sees fit in order to conclude with all due ceremony a treaty of commerce, as you seem to desire from your letter.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">While waiting for my court to examine and weigh maturely all the objects to be settled in a treaty of this nature, I believe, gentlemen, that it would be very advantageous for Americans to begin from this moment to frequent the ports of Sicily, particularly that of Messina, in order to establish forever commercial relations, which we can afterwards stipulate more precisely in the treaty to be concluded.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Permit me, gentlemen, to observe to you as well that to establish and carry on commerce of whatever extent it may be and in whatever country it may be, it is not necessary for it to be authorized beforehand by a treaty; it is sufficient for foreigners to be greeted with friendship and protected by law and by government. The proof is that all the nations that now conduct the most extensive trade in the Sicilies, such as the English, the French, the Genoans, the Venetians, the Ragusans, the Hamburgers, have no treaty of commerce with my court. Between it and France there are only the beginnings of a treaty, but the French are not at all waiting for it to be concluded in order to conduct a most extensive and profitable trade there.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">I have the honor of being with the greatest respect, gentlemen, your very humble and very obedient servant</p>
        <div class="closer">
          <div class="signed-multiple">
    <p class="signed multiple">de Pio, charg daffaires<br/>of the king of Naples</p>
  </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="docback">
